      <div id="faq-container">

        <details>
          <summary>What size generator do I need to run a whole house?</summary>
          <p>To run a whole house including major appliances like central air conditioning, electric ranges, and water heaters, you typically need a standby generator between 20,000 watts (20kW) and 26,000 watts (26kW). If you only want to power essential circuits (fridge, lights, furnace blower, well pump), a portable generator between 5,000 and 9,000 watts is usually sufficient.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>Is it worth buying a standby generator?</summary>
          <p>A standby generator is worth the investment if you live in an area prone to frequent or prolonged power outages, if you travel often and need to ensure your home (like sump pumps or heating systems) remains protected while you are away, or if someone in your home relies on medical equipment that requires constant electricity. While expensive upfront, they offer unparalleled convenience and peace of mind.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>How far should a generator be from a house?</summary>
          <p>For safety against carbon monoxide poisoning, a portable generator should be placed outdoors at least 20 feet away from your house. Ensure the exhaust is pointing away from any open doors, windows, and vents. Never run a generator inside a home, garage, basement, or partially enclosed space.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>Can I plug my generator directly into a wall outlet?</summary>
          <p>No, you should never plug a generator directly into a wall outlet. This illegal and highly dangerous practice is known as 'backfeeding.' It can send deadly voltage back into the public utility grid, endangering line workers attempting to restore power. You must connect appliances directly to the generator or use a professionally installed transfer switch.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>How long can a home generator run continuously?</summary>
          <p>A portable generator can run continuously as long as you keep refueling it, though you must shut it down periodically to check and change the oil (usually every 50 to 100 hours of operation). A standby generator connected to a natural gas line can run indefinitely, as long as the utility gas supply remains uninterrupted and proper maintenance schedules are followed.</p>
        </details>

      </div>
